attachments.title: 4th of July Fireworks Photos: 2016!
attachments.text:
First, it&rsquo;s with a heavy, magnesium-laden heart I bring some possibly serious&nbsp;news: this might&nbsp;be my final fireworks packaging post!?
Why? Why would this happen? I retire not due to a long-expected running-out of material &mdash; every year I think there won&rsquo;t be anything worth photographing and every year I&rsquo;m proven wrong &mdash; but rather, because of&nbsp;johnny law.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s the Last Year for Personal Fireworks in Vancouver&rdquo;&nbsp;explains:
This is the last year residents in Vancouver will be allowed to buy and use fireworks &ndash; and the last year for less than law abiding Oregonians who cross the Columbia River to purchase fireworks you can&rsquo;t buy in&nbsp;Portland.&nbsp;Last year, the Vancouver City Council passed an ordinance banning the personal use of any fireworks, including sparklers. They also banned the sale of fireworks in city&nbsp;limits.
Including sparklers!!!
Of course,&nbsp;Portland should&nbsp;still continue to sell the more common, less-lethal fireworks you can get in the grocery store &mdash; you know, the fancy fountains, the pop-its, the whistling pete&rsquo;s.
(A little tip about whistling pete&rsquo;s: flip &rsquo;em upside down and stick &rsquo;em in the holes in sewer grates for a good smoke/light show&nbsp;and cool effect-filtered freaky whistle.)
But when it comes to insane, amazing fireworks packaging, nothing beats the big.
It&rsquo;s not my place&nbsp;to pass judgement on the shriveled up, Raisinet-like hearts of the Vancouver City Council &mdash; I&nbsp;know&nbsp;they have their reasons, such as maybe owning dogs, having explosion-sensitive hearing aids, or something about a high chance of fire danger and personal injury to children something something &mdash; but I just wanted to let you know&hellip;
This could be it.&nbsp;So let&rsquo;s&nbsp;go.
Here are some photos of firework packaging in 2016.
(If you&rsquo;d like to enjoy the previous nine (!) years in this rich and ridiculous tradition, here you go:&nbsp;2007,&nbsp;2008,&nbsp;2009,&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;2011&nbsp;and then 2012,&nbsp;2013,&nbsp;2014,&nbsp;and 2015.)
Before We Begin&hellip;
Fire up iTunes or Spotify or Tidal or whatever and let&rsquo;s start a&hellip;

&hellip;because this year there was a fresh crop&nbsp;of:
More Exciting Movie&nbsp;Sequels!!

Increased Chance of a&nbsp;&lsquo;Hamilton&rsquo; Firework&nbsp;Next Year

Zany Animal Hijinx

The Italian Army

The First-Ever Font-Based Firework

A Cool Anime Aesthetic

Reese&rsquo;s Roller Coaster Tycoon

Finally An Answer to That Question, I Guess

Redundancy

Mobile Phones
(Wow they&rsquo;re getting five bars on that&nbsp;nightmare skull tube, that&rsquo;s good for Sprint!)
Everyone&rsquo;s Favorite

Exploding Affirmation

This &#128530;&#128530;&#128530;

More Booze

Some Now-Legal Recreationals

And More

The Most Painful Commentary&nbsp;Almost Certainly Delivered By a Vastly Underpaid Fireworks Packaging Graphic Designer Somewhere in China


And Finally&hellip; Honesty

Thank you all for joining me another year.
I hope you have a wonderful 4th of July!
